To find the constant $t$, we need to expand the left-hand side of the given equation and equate it to the right-hand side.

First, expand the left-hand side:

\begin{align*}
(5x^2 - 6x + 7)(4x^2 +tx + 10) &= 20x^4 + 5tx^3 + 50x^2 -24x^3 - 6tx^2 - 60x + 28x^2 + 7tx + 70 \\
&= 20x^4 + (5t-24)x^3 + (50-6t+28)x^2 + (7t-60)x + 70.
\end{align*}

Now equate the coefficients of the corresponding terms on the left-hand and right-hand sides:

\begin{align*}
&amp;\text{Coefficients of x^4: } 20 = 20 \text{ (match)} \\
&amp;\text{Coefficients of x^3: } 5t-24 = -54 \text{ (set up equation)} \\
&amp;\text{Coefficients of x^2: } 50-6t+28 = 114 \text{ (set up equation)} \\
&amp;\text{Coefficients of x: } 7t-60 = -102 \text{ (set up equation)} \\
&amp;\text{Constant terms: } 70 = 70 \text{ (match)}
\end{align*}

To find the value of $t$, we can use any of the above equations. Let's use the equation $5t-24 = -54$. Solving for $t$, we get:

\begin{align*}
5t-24 &= -54 \\
5t &= -54 + 24 \\
5t &= -30 \\
t &= \frac{-30}{5} \\
t &= \boxed{-6}
\end{align*}

We can verify this value of $t$ by plugging it into the other equations. For example, using the equation $7t-60 = -102$, we can verify that:

\begin{align*}
7(-6) - 60 &= -42 - 60 \\
-102 &= -102
\end{align*}

Since the equation holds true, we can be confident in our answer.
